snippet.textDisplay: I had a 98 ws6 with very low miles.   They do indeed have some flaws but overal I loved the car. For me the main flaws were the body started getting rust dots on the underbody and small rust spots under the hood even though it was a very low k car. They didn't seem to protect them as good as they should have. My T56 was a pig to shift especially when needed and that's a problem for a go fast car. The made in Mexico speakers blew early on mine I must have had it up too loud. Lots of little rattles but I don't think I have owned any car that didn't have some kind of noise. Fuel pump access is a bastard on these cars. On the ws6 the door panels can snap at the top but mine was ok so it must be from people slamming the doors. The engine bay is super tight. Getting to the clutch bleeder valve is super hard some people cut through the body to get to it just like the fuel pump.

snippet.textDisplay: I have a modded 98 Z28 with 51,000 miles. I don't race it as much as I used to. I mostly just bring it to car shows these days. But I've beaten some newer muscle cars on the road with it. When I say newer, I mean mostly cars that were manufactured in the first decade of the 2000's. And I've only added long tube headers, a large intake manifold, ported cylinder heads, 4:10 gears, and a loudmouth SLP exhaust. The thing is, these 4th gen Camaros weigh a lot less than the newer muscle cars, which helps things. New muscles cars are way too heavy for their own good.

snippet.textDisplay:
Why the 4.5 gen Camaro sucks:

Everything but the engine and transmission

Why it's awesome:

The engine and transmission... kinda. The 1st gen LS1 was a great stock performer... but the windowed mains and lack of bottom intermediate webbing between the main journals and sleeved block, meant power was limited. Though the 6-bolt mains were stable at high RPM, the block itself couldn't handle the strain.
